ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 4
 shows the optical characterization results of the NCD11 powders. As Fig. 4(a) shown, the trisodium citrate dihydrate and the conventional CDs (CD11) prepared with citric acid as carbon sources show no fluorescence emission under the 365 nm UV lamp. In contrast, strong yellow emissions from the NCD11 powders can be easily observed by the naked eyes under the same condition. The UV-vis absorption spectra are shown in Fig. 4(b). The NCD11 solution exhibits two strong absorption bands located at 325 nm and 400 nm, assigned to n-π* transitions of conjugated C=O and Mie scattering due to the extended conjugation in the CD structure, respectively [25]. For comparison, the NCD11 powders show a broader absorption even extending to visible area most probably owing to the interface interaction between the CDs and trisodium citrate matrix. The normalized fluorescence spectra of NCD11 with the different solute concentration in aqueous solution are shown in Fig. 4(c). With the decrease of NCD11 solute concentration, the emission maximum (525 nm) of the NCD11 powders has a remarkable blue-shift of 100 nm from that of dilute aqueous solution (425 nm), and the corresponding fluorescent colors change from yellow to blue similar to other reports [27,28]. The large blue-shift in the emission of the NCD11 from powder to aqueous solution probable results from the change of the interparticle distance. That is, the resonance energy transfers or re-absorption in the solid state is serious owing to the large overlaps between the absorption and emission spectra (375–600 nm) and small interparticle distance, making the long wavelength of emission comparatively enhanced. Nevertheless, the diluting effects with aqueous solution can effectively enlarge the interparticle distance and weaken the energy transfer in the CDs, causing a relative decrease in the long wavelength of emission. Furthermore, without the effect of uniform dispersal and space confinement from liquid (aqueous solution) or solid matrices (trisodium citrate crystals), the CD11 powders perform no fluorescence due to the aggregation-induced luminescence quenching. Interestingly, the PLQY of NCD11 powders could reach up to 21.6% under the 422 nm excitation, comparable to that of the NCD11 aqueous solution (0.1 mg mL−1) up to 20.8% under the same excitation (Table 1
). The high PLQYs are mainly on account of the forming of metal-cation-functionalized CDs when embedded in the trisodium citrate crystal matrix, which can induce less energy loss in the radiative recombination processes compared with the NCD11 aqueous solution due to the proton transfer dynamics always existing in protic solvent like water rather than in the solid-state crystal medium [25–28,42]. In addition, the fluorescence decay curves of NCD11 aqueous solution and powders have investigated for further verifying the intriguing fluorescence phenomenon as shown in Fig. 4(d). It is found the average lifetime of NCD11 powders (5.3 ns) is longer than that of the NCD11 solution (4.7 ns), deducing that the NCD11 should be well dispersed in trisodium citrate matrix with effectively preventing nonradiative recombination and energy loss induced by water molecules, further leading to the enhanced PLQYs.
